The 2020-21 staff were able to do some picture practice in the outdoors on Friday. We were missing one staff member (Katie Thompson) but the 4 new staff members along with returning members had a chance to learn a little about their cameras. The bonus was we could take off our masks outside!

In the group photo, the members are: (Back Row) Coy Jones; Dawson Dwyer, Co-Editor; Tolyn Ebberts; Rylee Kerr; Lucy Face; and Maggie Brungardt; (Front Row) Kelsey Johnson; Kaylie Reese, Co Editor; and Jadyn Troutman, Co-Editor.

It's going to be another great year in Yearbook Productions!

Mrs. Patton

post_text:
Virtual Graduation this Saturday, May 16th

11-1 Seniors can drive to City Hall and draw for Prizes from the Booster Club, please stay in your cars. Thank you Booster Club, you guys are the BEST!

11-1 Photos in Cap and Gown, after you receive your prizes, please get your photo taken by Mrs. Patton or yearbook staff member. She will be sharing these photos on Facebook later.

Congrats to WHS Class of 2020!!

We look forward to seeing to you on June 27th 2pm for a Traditional Graduation at the Football Stadium, if allowed by the state guidelines at that time. More info to come when the date gets closer.

post_text: Each week we will have a district challenge or activity for you to participate in should you desire. I would like for each of us this week to remember the many healthcare workers, emergency responders, and all of those individuals who are supporting, providing services or caring for those impacted by COVID-19. Tomorrow the MS and HS student council has teamed up to do a fundraiser for the Wellsville Friends Foundation.

This foundation collects money and gives it to families that are going through cancer to help supplement some of the added costs that go with treatment.

Students can pay $1 to wear a hat for the day. When they pay they will get a stamp on their hand to verify they have paid.

Student council members will be on the stage tomorrow morning collecting money.

post_text: I truly enjoyed the opportunity to attend the 2nd Annual WHS Concurrent Education Endowment Foundation Gala. This organization provides scholarships for WHS students taking technical college and/or college courses while in high school. Thank you to the foundation board of directors and all of the businesses and community members who so generously supported this effort! Your efforts are helping to move the needle in USD 289! Twenty seniors in the class of 2020 are on track to graduate with an Industry Recognized Certificate! It's A Great Day to Be an Eagle!

post_text: Wellsville FBLA had stellar performances from the FBLA members who attended the FBLA District VII Conference at Emporia State University on January 29. With 16 schools competing and over 400 competitors, Wellsville won the Top Overall Category with 824 accumulated points. 48 of the 54 from Wellsville who competed placed in the Top 10 in at least one or more of the 50+ business events that are offered. With eight districts in the state of Kansas, this competition allows students to prepare for competition at the Kansas FBLA State Leadership Conference in Topeka on March 30 and 31. At state, students will be vying for the opportunity to represent Kansas as competitors in their events at the national level. Wellsville FBLA members must place in the Top 2 in order to compete at the National Leadership Conference in Salt Lake City, Utah this summer. Thanks for your support of these great kids.

post_text:
January 2020 is School Board Recognition Month and our school district would like to thank each of our board of education members for their incredible service to our community and our public schools.

Their service to our school district is voluntary and they spend many, many hours serving our schools. They research, study and then discuss issues so that they can make informed decisions on countless complex challenges. Too often we forget about the personal sacrifices school board members make.

Our board of education includes:

Beth Watson
Dawn Whalen
Amanda Donovan
Gavin Fouts
Shane Pruitt
Jeremi Thompson
Todd Wilmarth

Each board member is a strong advocate for the success of every child in our schools. This January, please join us as we thank our school board members for volunteering their time, for fulfilling this very important civic responsibility, and for advocating on behalf of every child in our community. It’s A Great Day to Be an Eagle!

SIGNUP.COM
Meet with the Counselor

Wellsville USD 289 Counseling Department
October 2, 2019 at 2:31 PM ·

**SENIOR PARENTS**

Use the link below to schedule Senior Parent/Student Conference with Mrs. Buenger. Mrs. Buenger would love to talk to you and your student about their after high school plans! Whether your student is interested in a four year university, community college, or a trade school we can talk about what it will take to get there! If your student is unsure about their after-high school plans, we can also discuss how to start thinking about after high school.

We're using SignUp.com (the leading online SignUp and reminder tool) to organize our upcoming SignUps.

Here's how it works in 3 easy steps:

1) Click this link to see our SignUp on SignUp.com: https://signup.com/go/veqyzUp
2) Review the options listed and choose the spot(s) you like.
3) Sign up! It's Easy - you will NOT need to register an account or keep a password on SignUp.com.

Note: SignUp.com does not share your email address with anyone. If you prefer not to use your email address, please contact me and I can sign you up manually.

shared_text:
Kurt Neis‎Citizens for the future of Wellsville
September 27, 2019 at 2:25 PM ·

WELLSVILLE! We have teamed up with the Wellsville Fire Department for a FREE smoke detector event! Members of the lodge will be out with fire department members installing detectors on Oct 13th. The only requirements are that you own the home and have either no detectors, non working detectors or detectors more than 10 years old. You can tell the age of a detector by the manufacture date on it, if it has no date than its older than 10 years. If you are not in the Wellsville area for this event contact your local fire department about their program. Let's make our communities fire safe!
